    "plan_content": "## Summary\n\nHere's the plan for adding the `mistral-instruct-v3` handler:\n\n**Only one file changes: `common/chat.cpp`**\n\n### Two additions, zero modifications to existing code:\n\n**1. New handler function** (inserted between lines 940–942, after Ministral 3 / before GPT-OSS):\n\n`common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3()` that:\n- Iterates messages and collects `\"system\"` content into a `system_prompt` string\n- On the first `\"user\"` message, merges system prompt in (prepended with `\\n\\n`)\n- Calls the existing `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl()` with the adjusted messages (preserving BOS/EOS from the GGUF's Jinja template)\n- Returns `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` — simple format, no PEG parser required\n\n**2. Detection clause** in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` (inserted right after the Ministral 3 block at ~line 1644):\n\n```cpp\nif (src.find(\"[INST]\") != std::string::npos &&\n    src.find(\"[SYSTEM_PROMPT]\") == std::string::npos) {\n    LOG_DBG(\"Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\\n\");\n    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);\n}\n```\n\n**Why this correctly distinguishes from Ministral 3:** Ministral 3 templates carry `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (checked first at lines 1640–1643). Mistral Instruct v0.3 templates have `[INST]` but *no* `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, so they fall through to the new clause. No existing handler, detection block, or header is touched.",
